&quot;But death, unnatural death, isn't it all<br>
the same, whether or not it is a AK-47 or an M-16 that shoots you?&quot;<br><br>
Death is a natural process in the context of the human species, even that which arises out of combat in war because war is a natural process of humanity. In war, you are both the hunted and the hunter, 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. To survive war is an ultimate espression of that humanity. <br><br>
I chose not to lie across the Ho Chi Minh trail in protest of the war to get the gooks to stop moving arms, ammunition, and supplies to the VC and NVA because I would have been summarily shot in the midst of hysterical laughter. That would be suicide. That would have denied me the opportunity of kicking their ass and getting a psychological high from it all.<br><br>
Eventually, the cause of war becomes unimportant, and you just dig right in and do it.<br><br>
The risk of war is either life or death, physical and psychological. You are either better off living or better off dying, or wind up somewere in between.<br><br>
The process of lying across railroad tracks to stop a war is not war. It is a form of suicide. Although I am not familiar with the process of suicide, I can imagine that it has an entirely different expression of its outcome in terms of the individual.<br><br>
Are survivors of suicide attempts different from combat veterans?<br><br>
I bet they are.<br><br>
This is my intuitive feel. I am not an expert in suicide.  <br><br>
